[[Image:Pantani.jpg|thumb|right|Etzel emblem]]

'''Irgun''' ({{lang-he|ארגון}}), shorthand for '''Ha'Irgun Ha'Tsvai Ha'Leumi B'Eretz Yisrael''' ({{lang|he|הארגון הצבאי הלאומי בארץ ישראל}}, also spelled '''Ha'Irgun Ha'Zvai Ha'Leumi'''), Hebrew for "National Military Organization in the Land of Israel", was a clandestine militant [[Zionism|Zionist]] group that operated in [[Palestine (mandate)|Palestine]] from 1931 to 1948.  In Israel, this group is commonly referred to as '''Etzel''' ({{lang|he|אצ"ל}}), an acronym of the Hebrew initials. For secrecy reasons, in the time in which the Irgun operated, often people referred to the Irgun as (Haganah Bet) {{lang|he|הגנה ב}}, (Haganah Ha'leumit) {{lang|he|ההגנה הלאומית}} or {{lang|he|המעמד}} (Ha'ma'amad). Based on the premises formulated by [[Ze'ev Jabotinsky]] that "every [[Jew]] had the right to enter [[British Mandate of Palestine|Palestine]]; only active retaliation would deter the [[Arab]]s and the [[United Kingdom|British]]; only Jewish armed force would ensure the Jewish state", <ref>Howard Sachar: ''A History of the State of Israel'', pps 265-266</ref> the group made retaliation against Arab attacks a central part of their initial efforts as the armed expression of the nascent ideology of [[Revisionist Zionism]], it was a political predecessor movement to Israel's [[right-wing]] ''[[Herut]]'' (or "Freedom") party, which led to today's [[Likud]] party.

{| cellpadding="1" style="float: right; border: 1px solid #8888aa; background: #f7f8ff; padding: 5px; font-size: 95%; margin: 10px 2px 10px 2px;"
